  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \\(\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}\\), we can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Recognize that \\(x^{n-m} = \\frac{1}{x^{m-n}}\\):**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{x^{m-n}}}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Rewrite the second term using a common denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{x^{m-n}}} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{x^{m-n} + 1}{x^{m-n}}} = \\frac{x^{m-n}}{x^{m-n} + 1}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Combine the two fractions over a common denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{x^{m-n}}{1+x^{m-n}} = \\frac{1 + x^{m-n}}{(1 + x^{m-n})}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Simplify the resulting fraction:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1 + x^{m-n}}{1 + x^{m-n}} = 1\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the simplified form of the expression is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{1}\n\\]",
